None of the core Mongo classes (Mongo, MongoDB, MongoCollection) can be introspected at this time using PHP's Reflection API. As an example:
{code}

$classes = array(
    'Mongo',
    'MongoDB',
    'MongoCollection',
);
foreach ($classes as $class) {
    $r = new ReflectionClass($class);
    $c = $r->getConstructor();

    echo "Class $class expects " . $c->getNumberOfParameters() . " parameters\n";
    foreach ($c->getParameters() as $p) {
        echo $p->getPosition() . ': ' . $p->getName() . "\n";
    }
}
{code}

Results in:
{code}
Class Mongo expects 0 parameters
Class MongoDB expects 0 parameters
Class MongoCollection expects 0 parameters
{code}

(I'd expect each to report 2...)

This makes it difficult to use Reflection-based dependency injection strategies, as the number of arguments and argument names and positions cannot be determined.

{code}
<?php
$n = new MongoId();
var_export($n);

$a = MongoId::__set_state(array(
   '$id' => '4f06e55e44670ab92b000000',
));
var_dump($a);
?>
{code}

outputs
{code}
MongoId::__set_state(array(
   '$id' => '4f06e5f844670ade2b000000',
))
object(MongoId)#2 (1) {
  ["$id"]=>
  string(24) "000000000000000000000000"
}
{code}

